    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(4) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And blue, and purple, and scarlet.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The colours intended are probably a dark blue produced from indigo, which was the only blue known to the Egyptians, a purplish crimson derived from the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "murex trunculus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "the main source of the “Tyrian dye” of the ancients, and a scarlet furnished by the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "coccus ilicis, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or cochineal insect of the holm oak, which was largely employed in antiquity, though now superseded by the brighter tint obtained from the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "coccus cacti ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "of Mexico. Linen yarn of the three colours mentioned seems to have been what the people were asked to furnish (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 35:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 39:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Fine linen—i.e., white thread spun from flax, which is found to be the material of almost all the Egyptian dresses, mummy cloths, and other undyed fabrics. It is of a yellowish white, soft, and wonderfully fine and delicate. (See Wilkinson in Rawlinson’s Herodotus, vol. ii., p. 233).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Fine linen",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—i.e., white thread spun from flax, which is found to be the material of almost all the Egyptian dresses, mummy cloths, and other undyed fabrics. It is of a yellowish white, soft, and wonderfully fine and delicate. (See Wilkinson in Rawlinson’s ",
