  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 4.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And blue, and purple, and scarlet",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Cloths of these three colours seem to be meant. The material was probably wool; the blue dye probably indigo, which was the ordinary blue dye of Egypt; the purple was no doubt derived from one or other of the shell-fish so well-known to the Syrians (of which the one most used was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the Murex trunculus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and was of a warm reddish hue, not far from crimson; the scarlet (literally, \"scarlet ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "worm\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "worm",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " scarlet,\") was the produce of the  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Corcus ilicis",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or cochineal insect of the holm oak, which has now been superseded by the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Coccus cacti",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or cochineal insect of the prickly pear, introduced into Europe from Mexico. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And fine linen",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word used is Egyptian. It seems to have designated properly the fine linen spun from flax in Egypt, which was seldom dyed. and was of a beautiful soft white hue. The fineness of the material is extraordinary, equalling that of the best Indian muslins (Wilkinson's ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Ancient",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Egyptians",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", vol. 3. p. 121). It would seem that the Israelite women spun the thread from the flax (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 35:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and that the skilled workmen employed by Moses wove the thread into linen (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ib",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 35). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And goat's hair",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The soft inner wool of the Angora goat was also spun by the women into a fine worsted (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ib",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 26), which was woven into cloths, used especially as coverings for tents. Exodus 25:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
